#!/usr/bin/env bash
# Follows the superpowers plugin hook pattern.
# See: https://github.com/superpowers/superpowers (SessionStart hook)
#
# NOTE: This hook will not fire automatically without plugin infrastructure.
# It requires either:
#   (a) A superpowers-compatible plugin host that reads hooks.json, OR
#   (b) Manual integration into your tool's hook system (e.g., sourcing this
#       script from your tool's session-init pipeline).

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# JSON escape helper — bash parameter substitution (not character loops).
# Handles: backslash, double-quote, newline, carriage return, tab.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
escape_for_json() {
  local s="$1"
  s="${s//\\/\\\\}"    # \ → \\
  s="${s//\"/\\\"}"    # " → \"
  s="${s//$'\n'/\\n}"  # newline → \n
  s="${s//$'\r'/\\r}"  # CR → \r
  s="${s//$'\t'/\\t}"  # tab → \t
  printf '%s' "$s"
}

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Iron-law content injected at every session start
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
read -r -d '' CONTENT << 'ENDOFCONTENT'
<EXTREMELY_IMPORTANT>
You are working on the Particle-Viewer project. The following laws are non-negotiable and override any tendency toward convenience, speed, or assumption.

## Iron Law 1 — TDD: Test First, Always

YOU MUST write a failing test before writing any production code. No exceptions.

Sequence: write the test → watch it fail → write the minimum code to pass → refactor.

If you find yourself thinking "I'll add the test after" or "this is too simple to test" — that thought is rationalization. Stop. Write the test first. See the `testing` skill for patterns and conventions.

## Iron Law 2 — VERIFICATION: Run It Before You Claim It

YOU MUST run the verification command in this session before claiming any work is complete.

Saying "should work", "probably passes", or expressing satisfaction BEFORE running = a violation.

Run this exact command, read the output, then report:
```
cmake --build build && ./build/tests/ParticleViewerTests
```

Silence is not confirmation. Empty output gets a second check. No exceptions.

## Iron Law 3 — DEBUGGING: Root Cause Before Fix

YOU MUST trace a failure to its root cause before proposing or applying a fix.

Proposing a fix you haven't traced = symptom patching. It will recur.

Steps: reproduce it → read the actual error (not the summary) → trace the call path → identify the root → fix the root. See the `systematic-debugging` skill.

---

## Skill Auto-Load Table

Read the required skill(s) BEFORE acting — not after, not during:

| Task type                  | Skills to read BEFORE acting               |
|----------------------------|--------------------------------------------|
| Any implementation         | `execution`                                |
| Writing/editing C++        | `execution`, `code-quality`               |
| Writing/editing tests      | `execution`, `code-quality`, `testing`    |
| Debugging a failure        | `systematic-debugging`                     |
| Claiming work is done      | `verification-before-completion`           |
| Creating PR or commit      | `versioning`                               |
| CI/CD changes              | `workflow`                                 |
| Build/dependency changes   | `build`                                    |
| Documentation changes      | `documentation`                            |

---

## Pre-Commit Gate

Before EVERY commit, YOU MUST run both commands and confirm they pass:

```
find src tests -name "*.cpp" -o -name "*.hpp" | xargs clang-format -i
cmake --build build && ./build/tests/ParticleViewerTests
```

CI will reject unformatted code. Tests must pass before pushing. No staged commits on failing builds.

---

## Commitment Mechanism

When you load a skill, announce it: "I am using the [skill-name] skill to [purpose]." This is not optional.
</EXTREMELY_IMPORTANT>
ENDOFCONTENT

context=$(escape_for_json "$CONTENT")

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Output platform-specific JSON
#   - Cursor:  { "context": "..." }         (CURSOR_PLUGIN_ROOT is set)
#   - Claude:  { "context": "..." }         (CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT is set)
#   - Copilot CLI fallback: { "additionalContext": "..." }
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
if [[ -n "${CURSOR_PLUGIN_ROOT:-}" ]]; then
  printf '{"context":"%s"}\n' "$context"
elif [[ -n "${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT:-}" ]]; then
  printf '{"context":"%s"}\n' "$context"
else
  printf '{"additionalContext":"%s"}\n' "$context"
fi
